                    </div>
                    <span>One thing in particular I like about Solzhenitsyn is that he manages to sympathise with every charactor. I remember in the First Circle when in his description of Stalin he calls him a lonely man...(maybe i misquote). <P>Somethings in previous reviews stood out to me. Firstly that Cancer ward will remain the most relevant of his novels due to the fact that Cancer (and illness) is something that will remain through time. Personally, I grew fonder of the first circle yet how can I possibly judge which is the greater novel. Maybe Solzhenitsyn can give a good opinion on what he thinks but I have no idea of the relevant depths of all his works. I don't think any of his books will lose relevance though.<BR>Another reviewer said whats important is not that we live but how we live. I agree that the most important thing is how and not what. But surely it is important that we are living? That life should be treasured, I liked what he said about good guy and bad guy. Surely noone is free from evil? Maybe he(the reviewer) means whats important is how as opposed to that we make sure we contiue to live. In that case I agree. But if he means that we have to live in a certain way then I'm not sure if I agree with that because how could you forgive one another?<BR>Another thing is that some people have compared Kostoglotov with Solzhenitsyn. Calling Kost an optimistic realist. But Kost defends the persuit for happiness, which I don't think Solzhenitsyn does (Read Gulag chapter the ascent). And I think Shulubin holds a lot of Solzhenitsyn's views. But this is more a question and I would like to hear other peoples' opinions. At first I thought that Kostol was like Solzhenitsyn but now I think less so. To me Nerzhin(in the first circle) seems to be a lot more like him? Infact at times I sense that Solzhenitsyn gets frustrated with Kostol attitude? <BR>One more thing, I think it is worth looking at different translations(not to the above but generally).</span>
                  
                    <div class="CustomerReviewSummary">Excellent</div>
                    <div>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Rating: </span>
